post_cb({"2709306": {"ParentId": "2709283", "CommentCount": "2", "Body": "<p>Deleting via  a void pointer is undefined, as is doing anything else via a void pointer except explicitly converting it to another kind of pointer.</p>\n", "Id": "2709306", "PostTypeId": "2", "OwnerDisplayName": "anon", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2010-04-25T18:10:21.833", "LastActivityDate": "2010-04-25T18:10:21.833"}, "2709283": {"CommentCount": "2", "ViewCount": "1877", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "4370109", "CreationDate": "2010-04-25T18:06:37.210", "LastActivityDate": "2015-07-06T19:03:41.880", "Title": "C++ delete static_cast<void*> (pointer) behavior", "AcceptedAnswerId": "2709295", "LastEditDate": "2015-07-06T19:03:41.880", "Id": "2709283", "Score": "4", "Body": "<p>suppose the code does the following:</p>\n<pre><code>T *pointer = new T();\ndelete static_cast&lt;void*&gt;(pointer);\n</code></pre>\n<p>what is result?  Undefined, memory leak, memory is deleted?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><casting><delete-operator>", "OwnerUserId": "206328", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_2709283_2709295_0": {"section_id": 6107, "quality": 0.875, "length": 35}, "so_2709283_2709295_1": {"section_id": 6105, "quality": 0.7333333333333333, "length": 11}}, "n3337": {"so_2709283_2709295_0": {"section_id": 5873, "quality": 0.875, "length": 35}, "so_2709283_2709295_1": {"section_id": 5871, "quality": 0.6666666666666666, "length": 10}}, "n4659": {"so_2709283_2709295_0": {"section_id": 7604, "quality": 0.875, "length": 35}, "so_2709283_2709295_1": {"section_id": 7602, "quality": 0.7333333333333333, "length": 11}}}, "2709295": {"ParentId": "2709283", "CommentCount": "1", "Body": "<p>The behavior is undefined.  Concerning the delete expression, the C++ standard says:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_2709283_2709295_0\">In the first alternative (<em>delete object</em>), if the static type of the operand is different from its dynamic type, the static type shall be a base class of the operand\u2019s dynamic type and the static type shall have a virtual destructor or the behavior is undefined.  In the second alternative (<em>delete array</em>) if the dynamic type of the object to be deleted differs from its static type, the behavior is undefined.  (\u00a75.3.5/3)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Then the footnote to this paragraph clearly states:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_2709283_2709295_1\">This implies that an object cannot be deleted using a pointer of type <code>void*</code> because there are no objects of type <code>void</code> (note 73).</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "OwnerUserId": "151292", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "2709295", "Score": "7", "CreationDate": "2010-04-25T18:08:25.843", "LastActivityDate": "2010-04-25T18:08:25.843"}});